**Theorem 5.3.2 (Global Causal-Safety Coherence).** If local archive sections agree on overlaps and each has a valid safety certificate, then the glued global section has a valid certificate and preserves causal consistency.

*Proof.* By the sheaf condition (Theorem 5.3.1), the glued section $(f, \mathcal{C}, w, c)$ exists. Validity of $\mathcal{C}$ follows from the validity of local certificates and the hash-chain structure: each local certificate's $H_{\text{prev}}$ matches the hash of the previous global certificate, ensuring the chain is unbroken. Causal consistency $w$ is preserved by witness composition. ∎

**Corollary 5.3.1 (Auditability).** Any external auditor possessing the certificate chain and the set of local witnesses can verify the global causal-safety consistency without re-running simulations or re-verifying constraints from scratch.

*Proof.* The auditor checks: (1) hash-chain integrity of certificates, (2) signature validity on each certificate, (3) proof checker acceptance of each $\pi$, (4) witness compositionality on overlaps. All are efficient operations. ∎

