## 9.2 Hash-Chained Ledger and Tamper-Evidence

**Definition 9.2.1 (Causal-Safety Ledger).** The ledger $\mathcal{L}$ is an ordered sequence of valid safety certificates:
$$\mathcal{L} = (\mathcal{C}_0, \mathcal{C}_1, \dots, \mathcal{C}_N).$$
The ledger is **valid** if for all $k \in \{1, \dots, N\}$:
1.  $\mathcal{C}_k.H_{\text{prev}} = H(\mathcal{C}_{k-1})$.
2.  $\text{Verify}(pk, \mathcal{C}_k.\text{body}, \mathcal{C}_k.\sigma_k) = \text{True}$.
3.  $\text{CheckProof}(\mathcal{C}_k.H_{\text{proof}}, \mathcal{C}_{k-1}.H_{\text{ctx}}) = \text{True}$ (the proof validates the transition from $\mathcal{K}_{k-1}$ to $\mathcal{K}_k$).

**Theorem 9.2.1 (Ledger Integrity).** Assume $H$ is collision-resistant. If an adversary modifies any certificate $\mathcal{C}_j$ in a valid ledger $\mathcal{L}$ to $\mathcal{C}_j'$, then the modified ledger $\mathcal{L}'$ will be invalid unless the adversary also modifies all subsequent certificates $\mathcal{C}_{j+1}, \dots, \mathcal{C}_N$ and can forge signatures for each.

*Proof.* Let $\mathcal{C}_j$ be modified to $\mathcal{C}_j'$. Then $H(\mathcal{C}_j') \neq H(\mathcal{C}_j)$ with overwhelming probability. Certificate $\mathcal{C}_{j+1}$ contains $H_{\text{prev}} = H(\mathcal{C}_j)$. For $\mathcal{L}'$ to be valid, $\mathcal{C}_{j+1}$ must be updated to $\mathcal{C}_{j+1}'$ with $H_{\text{prev}}' = H(\mathcal{C}_j')$. This requires recomputing the hash and forging the signature $\sigma_{j+1}'$. By induction, all subsequent certificates must be forged. Since signature forgery is computationally infeasible (EUF-CMA), the tampering is detectable. ∎

**Corollary 9.2.1 (Audit Efficiency).** An auditor verifying the ledger at step $N$ needs only to verify $\mathcal{C}_N$ and a logarithmic number of hash links if Merkle proofs are used for context transitions. The full history is implicitly verified by the chain structure.

