## 9.3 Revocation Protocol and Graceful Degradation

No safety system can guarantee zero violations indefinitely. Sensors fail, environments exhibit unmodeled physics, and adversarial attacks may succeed. The ledger must support **revocation** to mark the end of a trusted safety lineage.

**Definition 9.3.1 (Revocation Certificate).** A revocation certificate $\mathcal{R}$ is a special certificate structure:
$$\mathcal{R} = \big( H_{\text{prev}}, \text{id}_{\text{rev}}, t_{\text{rev}}, \text{reason}, \sigma_{\text{rev}} \big),$$
where:
1.  $H_{\text{prev}}$ is the hash of the last valid safety certificate $\mathcal{C}_{\text{last}}$.
2.  $\text{reason} \in \{\text{collision}, \text{sensor\_fault}, \text{adversarial}, \text{manual}\}$ indicates the cause.
3.  $\sigma_{\text{rev}}$ is signed by the system's private key (or a hardware kill-switch key).

**Protocol 9.3.1 (Revocation Trigger).** Upon detecting a safety violation (e.g., $S(\theta) > 0$ despite certificate validity) or critical component failure:
1.  Immediately halt all adaptive processes (freeze $\mathcal{K}$).
2.  Generate $\mathcal{R}$ referencing the current ledger head.
3.  Append $\mathcal{R}$ to the ledger $\mathcal{L}$.
4.  Transition to **Safe Mode**: only Spinal Core reflexes (Chapter 1) remain active; all Deliberative and Reactive adaptations are disabled.

**Theorem 9.3.1 (Revocation Integrity).** Once a revocation certificate $\mathcal{R}$ is appended to a valid ledger, no future safety certificate $\mathcal{C}_{\text{new}}$ can be validly chained from any certificate preceding $\mathcal{R}$ without detection.

*Proof.* Any valid $\mathcal{C}_{\text{new}}$ must reference $H_{\text{prev}} = H(\mathcal{R})$ or a subsequent certificate. Since $\mathcal{R}$ marks the transition to Safe Mode, the system logic prevents generation of $\mathcal{C}_{\text{new}}$ until a human-in-the-loop resets the ledger (issuing a new genesis certificate $\mathcal{C}_0'$). Attempting to chain from $\mathcal{C}_{\text{last}}$ (before $\mathcal{R}$) would require ignoring $\mathcal{R}$, which any auditor checking the full ledger would detect. ∎

**Definition 9.3.2 (Graceful Degradation).** In Safe Mode, the system operates with:
1.  Fixed policy $\pi_{\text{safe}}$ (verified at genesis).
2.  Maximum conservatism $\kappa = 100$ (Chapter 2).
3.  No learning or adaptation ($\Delta = \mathbf{0}$).

This ensures that even after revocation, the system remains fail-safe until repaired.

