## 10.6 Limitations and Boundary Conditions

No theoretical framework is without limitations. We explicitly state the boundary conditions under which GCMSI guarantees hold.

### 10.6.1 Sandbox Fidelity Assumption
**Limitation:** Theorem 10.2.1 relies on Assumption 8.2.1 ($\varepsilon$-bounded sandbox deviation). If the real world diverges from the sandbox by more than $\varepsilon$ (e.g., unmodeled physics, adversarial perturbations), the probabilistic bound may be violated.
**Mitigation:** The Meta-Safety Layer dynamically increases $\kappa$ when novelty is detected, effectively increasing the safety margin to absorb larger $\varepsilon$. Additionally, online system identification can update $\varepsilon$ estimates (Future Work, Chapter 11).

### 10.6.2 Lipschitz Constant Estimation
**Limitation:** Safety proofs require known Lipschitz constants $L$ for constraints (Theorem 8.2.1). For complex neural components, $L$ may be large or difficult to compute exactly.
**Mitigation:** Use conservative upper bounds for $L$ (e.g., via spectral normalization). This reduces performance (larger margins) but preserves safety.

### 10.6.3 Symmetry Approximation
**Limitation:** Chapter 6 assumes exact or $\varepsilon$-approximate symmetries. In highly asymmetric environments (e.g., cluttered indoor spaces), symmetry compression may lose fidelity, leading to false negatives in verification.
**Mitigation:** The Novelty-Dependent Symmetry Group (Definition 6.5.1) disables compression when novelty is high, reverting to full verification.

### 10.6.4 Computational Overhead
**Limitation:** Proof generation and ledger management introduce latency. For high-frequency control loops (1 kHz Spinal Core), this overhead is unacceptable.
**Mitigation:** GCMSI is designed for the Deliberative (10 Hz) and Reactive (100 Hz) brains. The Spinal Core uses hard-coded reflexes without ledger updates, ensuring hard real-time performance (Chapter 1).

### 10.6.5 Cryptographic Assumptions
**Limitation:** Ledger integrity relies on collision-resistant hashes and unforgeable signatures. Quantum computing could potentially break these assumptions in the future.
**Mitigation:** Post-quantum cryptographic schemes (e.g., lattice-based signatures) can be substituted without changing the theoretical framework.

